	<article class="post-3492 post type-post status-publish hentry" id="post-3492">
	<header class="postHeader">
				<div class="postKicker">
					</div>
				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Readers Respond: On Long-Term Unemployment</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Marie Tessier			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-09-25T15:36:12+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">September 25, 2014 11:36 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">September 25, 2014 11:36 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//op-talk.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/09/25/readers-respond-on-long-term-unemployment/" data-title="Readers Respond: On Long-Term Unemployment" data-description="Readers wrote on parables, responsibility and balance in comments on Paul Krugmanâs Op-Ed âThose Lazy Jobless.â ">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Given the almost religious fervor, it might have been a debate about old-fashioned creation theology.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Instead, it was a dispute over job creation theology inspired by House Speaker John Boehner, who recently told a conservative audience that unemployed workers would ârather just sit aroundâ than find paying work. Paul Krugmanâs ensuing column, â<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/09/22/opinion/paul-krugman-those-lazy-jobless.html">Those Lazy Jobless</a>,â inspired 1,500 responses.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âEver since a financial crisis plunged us into recession it has been a nonstop refrain on the right that the unemployed arenât trying hard enough,â Mr. Krugman wrote. âThe urge to blame the victims of a depressed economy has proved impervious to logic and evidence.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">People who have been out of work for longer than six months need to think about retraining rather than seeking extended benefits, some readers said. One appealed to the parable about âteaching a man to fish.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWhat people on the right believe is that if you are poor and unemployed, then it is your personal responsibility to fix that situation,â <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/09/22/opinion/paul-krugman-those-lazy-jobless.html?comments#permid=12864258">Frank in the United States wrote</a>. âIt is not the governmentâs responsibility.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">That âteach a man to fishâ allusion prompted dozens of indignant responses, including from many who wrote that structural economic conditions are the problem, not a supposed lack of individual responsibility.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThere are thousands of skilled workers looking for work,â <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/09/22/opinion/paul-krugman-those-lazy-jobless.html?comments#permid=12864258:12864320">Tom wrote from New York</a>. âThey already know how to fish, there arenât any fish!â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Others replied with a Christian story. âIf you remember, Jesus fed fish (and some loaves!) to the multitudes,â <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/09/22/opinion/paul-krugman-those-lazy-jobless.html?comments#permid=12864258:12869568">EConnie wrote from Florida</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Krugman asked, âWhy is there so much animus against the unemployed?â Adding that a âblame-the-victimâ message has been used to justify sharp cuts in benefits for the jobless.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Some readers wrote that Mr. Boehner knows there are twice as many job seekers as jobs available but has political motives for denigrating people who are out of work.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âBoehner knows the facts as well as anybody,â <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/09/22/opinion/paul-krugman-those-lazy-jobless.html?comments#permid=12869293">Stan Jacobs wrote from Ann Arbor, Mich.</a> âHe also knows that his audience wants very hard to feel that if people are suffering because of joblessness or low wages it&#8217;s their own fault.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Some readers allowed for merit in the arguments of both right and left.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe Republicans think everyone who is unemployed is a âbum,ââ <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/09/22/opinion/paul-krugman-those-lazy-jobless.html?comments#permid=12866041">Nigel wrote from New York</a>. âThe Democrats think that no one is. The truth is somewhere in the middle.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Krugman wrote that misconceptions about unemployment persist, despite the fact that only 26 percent of unemployed people are now receiving benefits. Characterizing jobless workers as âlazyâ doesnât make sense, many readers agreed, given the way the insurance benefit works.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âTo collect unemployment, one has to have held a full-time job for six months or more,â<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/09/22/opinion/paul-krugman-those-lazy-jobless.html?comments#permid=12865845"> Cindy Allen in Gainesville, Fla., wrote</a>. âTo call these people âslackersâ or âlazyâ is unconscionable.â</p>
	</div>
